# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chain-of-density
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Text summarization is usually implemented by natural language processing methods, designed to locate the most informative sentences in a given document.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] On the other hand, visual content can be summarized using computer vision algorithms.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Image summarization is the subject of ongoing research; existing approaches typically attempt to display the most representative images from a given image collection, or generate a video that only includes the most important content from the entire collection.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Video summarization algorithms identify and extract from the original video content the most important frames (*key-frames*), and/or the most important video segments (*key-shots*), normally in a temporally ordered fashion.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Video summaries simply retain a carefully selected subset of the original video frames and, therefore, are not identical to the output of video synopsis algorithms, where *new* video frames are being synthesized based on the original video content.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In 2022 Google Docs released an automatic summarization feature.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] There are two general approaches to automatic summarization: extraction and abstraction.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Here, content is extracted from the original data, but the extracted content is not modified in any way.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Examples of extracted content include key-phrases that can be used to "tag" or index a text document, or key sentences (including headings) that collectively comprise an abstract, and representative images or video segments, as stated above.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For text, extraction is analogous to the process of skimming, where the summary (if available), headings and subheadings, figures, the first and last paragraphs of a section, and optionally the first and last sentences in a paragraph are read before one chooses to read the entire document in detail.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Other examples of extraction that include key sequences of text in terms of clinical relevance (including patient/problem, intervention, and outcome).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Abstractive summarization methods generate new text that did not exist in the original text.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Abstractive methods build an internal semantic representation of the original content (often called a language model), and then use this representation to create a summary that is closer to what a human might express.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Abstraction may transform the extracted content by paraphrasing sections of the source document, to condense a text more strongly than extraction.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Such transformation, however, is computationally much more challenging than extraction, involving both natural language processing and often a deep understanding of the domain of the original text in cases where the original document relates to a special field of knowledge.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] "Paraphrasing" is even more difficult to apply to images and videos, which is why most summarization systems are extractive.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Approaches aimed at higher summarization quality rely on combined software and human effort.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In Machine Aided Human Summarization, extractive techniques highlight candidate passages for inclusion (to which the human adds or removes text).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In Human Aided Machine Summarization, a human post-processes software output, in the same way that one edits the output of automatic translation by Google Translate.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] There are broadly two types of extractive summarization tasks depending on what the summarization program focuses on.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The first is *generic summarization*, which focuses on obtaining a generic summary or abstract of the collection (whether documents, or sets of images, or videos, news stories etc.).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The second is *query relevant summarization*, sometimes called *query-based summarization*, which summarizes objects specific to a query.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Summarization systems are able to create both query relevant text summaries and generic machine-generated summaries depending on what the user needs.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] An example of a summarization problem is document summarization, which attempts to automatically produce an abstract from a given document.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Sometimes one might be interested in generating a summary from a single source document, while others can use multiple source documents (for example, a cluster of articles on the same topic).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] This problem is called multi-document summarization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] A related application is summarizing news articles.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Imagine a system, which automatically pulls together news articles on a given topic (from the web), and concisely represents the latest news as a summary.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Image collection summarization is another application example of automatic summarization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] It consists in selecting a representative set of images from a larger set of images.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] A summary in this context is useful to show the most representative images of results in an image collection exploration system.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Video summarization is a related domain, where the system automatically creates a trailer of a long video.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] This also has applications in consumer or personal videos, where one might want to skip the boring or repetitive actions.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Similarly, in surveillance videos, one would want to extract important and suspicious activity, while ignoring all the boring and redundant frames captured.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] At a very high level, summarization algorithms try to find subsets of objects (like set of sentences, or a set of images), which cover information of the entire set.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] These algorithms model notions like diversity, coverage, information and representativeness of the summary.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Query based summarization techniques, additionally model for relevance of the summary with the query.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Some techniques and algorithms which naturally model summarization problems are TextRank and PageRank, Submodular set function, Determinantal point process, maximal marginal relevance (MMR) etc.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] You are given a piece of text, such as a journal article, and you must produce a list of keywords or key[phrase]s that capture the primary topics discussed in the text.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In the case of research articles, many authors provide manually assigned keywords, but most text lacks pre-existing keyphrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For example, news articles rarely have keyphrases attached, but it would be useful to be able to automatically do so for a number of applications discussed below.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] A keyphrase extractor might select "Army Corps of Engineers", "President Bush", "New Orleans", and "defective flood-control pumps" as keyphrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] These are pulled directly from the text.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In contrast, an abstractive keyphrase system would somehow internalize the content and generate keyphrases that do not appear in the text, but more closely resemble what a human might produce, such as "political negligence" or "inadequate protection from floods".
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Abstraction requires a deep understanding of the text, which makes it difficult for a computer system.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] They can enable document browsing by providing a short summary, improve information retrieval (if documents have keyphrases assigned, a user could search by keyphrase to produce more reliable hits than a full-text search), and be employed in generating index entries for a large text corpus.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Depending on the different literature and the definition of key terms, words or phrases, keyword extraction is a highly related theme.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Beginning with the work of Turney, many researchers have approached keyphrase extraction as a supervised machine learning problem.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Given a document, we construct an example for each unigram, bigram, and trigram found in the text (though other text units are also possible, as discussed below).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] We then compute various features describing each example (e.g., does the phrase begin with an upper-case letter?).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] We assume there are known keyphrases available for a set of training documents.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Using the known keyphrases, we can assign positive or negative labels to the examples.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Then we learn a classifier that can discriminate between positive and negative examples as a function of the features.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Some classifiers make a binary classification for a test example, while others assign a probability of being a keyphrase.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For instance, in the above text, we might learn a rule that says phrases with initial capital letters are likely to be keyphrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] After training a learner, we can select keyphrases for test documents in the following manner.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] We apply the same example-generation strategy to the test documents, then run each example through the learner.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] We can determine the keyphrases by looking at binary classification decisions or probabilities returned from our learned model.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] If probabilities are given, a threshold is used to select the keyphrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Keyphrase extractors are generally evaluated using precision and recall.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Precision measures how many of the proposed keyphrases are actually correct.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Recall measures how many of the true keyphrases your system proposed.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The two measures can be combined in an F-score, which is the harmonic mean of the two (*F* = 2*PR*/(*P* + *R*) ).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Matches between the proposed keyphrases and the known keyphrases can be checked after stemming or applying some other text normalization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Designing a supervised keyphrase extraction system involves deciding on several choices (some of these apply to unsupervised, too).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The first choice is exactly how to generate examples.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Turney and others have used all possible unigrams, bigrams, and trigrams without intervening punctuation and after removing stopwords.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Hulth showed that you can get some improvement by selecting examples to be sequences of tokens that match certain patterns of part-of-speech tags.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Ideally, the mechanism for generating examples produces all the known labeled keyphrases as candidates, though this is often not the case.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For example, if we use only unigrams, bigrams, and trigrams, then we will never be able to extract a known keyphrase containing four words.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] However, generating too many examples can also lead to low precision.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] We also need to create features that describe the examples and are informative enough to allow a learning algorithm to discriminate keyphrases from non- keyphrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Typically features involve various term frequencies (how many times a phrase appears in the current text or in a larger corpus), the length of the example, relative position of the first occurrence, various Boolean syntactic features (e.g., contains all caps), etc.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The Turney paper used about 12 such features.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Hulth uses a reduced set of features, which were found most successful in the KEA (Keyphrase Extraction Algorithm) work derived from Turney's seminal paper.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In the end, the system will need to return a list of keyphrases for a test document, so we need to have a way to limit the number.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Ensemble methods (i.e., using votes from several classifiers) have been used to produce numeric scores that can be thresholded to provide a user-provided number of keyphrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] This is the technique used by Turney with C4.5 decision trees.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Hulth used a single binary classifier so the learning algorithm implicitly determines the appropriate number.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Once examples and features are created, we need a way to learn to predict keyphrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Virtually any supervised learning algorithm could be used, such as decision trees, Naive Bayes, and rule induction.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In the case of Turney's GenEx algorithm, a genetic algorithm is used to learn parameters for a domain-specific keyphrase extraction algorithm.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The extractor follows a series of heuristics to identify keyphrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The genetic algorithm optimizes parameters for these heuristics with respect to performance on training documents with known key phrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Another keyphrase extraction algorithm is TextRank.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] While supervised methods have some nice properties, like being able to produce interpretable rules for what features characterize a keyphrase, they also require a large amount of training data.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Many documents with known keyphrases are needed.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Furthermore, training on a specific domain tends to customize the extraction process to that domain, so the resulting classifier is not necessarily portable, as some of Turney's results demonstrate.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Unsupervised keyphrase extraction removes the need for training data.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] It approaches the problem from a different angle.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Instead of trying to learn explicit features that characterize keyphrases, the TextRank algorithm exploits the structure of the text itself to determine keyphrases that appear "central" to the text in the same way that PageRank selects important Web pages.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Recall this is based on the notion of "prestige" or "recommendation" from social networks.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In this way, TextRank does not rely on any previous training data at all, but rather can be run on any arbitrary piece of text, and it can produce output simply based on the text's intrinsic properties.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Thus the algorithm is easily portable to new domains and languages.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] TextRank is a general purpose graph-based ranking algorithm for NLP.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Essentially, it runs PageRank on a graph specially designed for a particular NLP task.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For keyphrase extraction, it builds a graph using some set of text units as vertices.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Edges are based on some measure of semantic or lexical similarity between the text unit vertices.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Unlike PageRank, the edges are typically undirected and can be weighted to reflect a degree of similarity.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The vertices should correspond to what we want to rank.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Potentially, we could do something similar to the supervised methods and create a vertex for each unigram, bigram, trigram, etc.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] However, to keep the graph small, the authors decide to rank individual unigrams in a first step, and then include a second step that merges highly ranked adjacent unigrams to form multi-word phrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] This has a nice side effect of allowing us to produce keyphrases of arbitrary length.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For example, if we rank unigrams and find that "advanced", "natural", "language", and "processing" all get high ranks, then we would look at the original text and see that these words appear consecutively and create a final keyphrase using all four together.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Note that the unigrams placed in the graph can be filtered by part of speech.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The authors found that adjectives and nouns were the best to include.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Thus, some linguistic knowledge comes into play in this step.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Edges are created based on word co-occurrence in this application of TextRank.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Two vertices are connected by an edge if the unigrams appear within a window of size N in the original text.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Thus, "natural" and "language" might be linked in a text about NLP.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] "Natural" and "processing" would also be linked because they would both appear in the same string of N words.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] These edges build on the notion of "text cohesion" and the idea that words that appear near each other are likely related in a meaningful way and "recommend" each other to the reader.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Since this method simply ranks the individual vertices, we need a way to threshold or produce a limited number of keyphrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The technique chosen is to set a count T to be a user-specified fraction of the total number of vertices in the graph.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Then the top T vertices/unigrams are selected based on their stationary probabilities.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] A post- processing step is then applied to merge adjacent instances of these T unigrams.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] As a result, potentially more or less than T final keyphrases will be produced, but the number should be roughly proportional to the length of the original text.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] It is not initially clear why applying PageRank to a co-occurrence graph would produce useful keyphrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] One way to think about it is the following.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] A word that appears multiple times throughout a text may have many different co-occurring neighbors.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For example, in a text about machine learning, the unigram "learning" might co-occur with "machine", "supervised", "un-supervised", and "semi-supervised" in four different sentences.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Thus, the "learning" vertex would be a central "hub" that connects to these other modifying words.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Running PageRank/TextRank on the graph is likely to rank "learning" highly.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Similarly, if the text contains the phrase "supervised classification", then there would be an edge between "supervised" and "classification".
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] If "classification" appears several other places and thus has many neighbors, its importance would contribute to the importance of "supervised".
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] If it ends up with a high rank, it will be selected as one of the top T unigrams, along with "learning" and probably "classification".
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In the final post-processing step, we would then end up with keyphrases "supervised learning" and "supervised classification".
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In short, the co-occurrence graph will contain densely connected regions for terms that appear often and in different contexts.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] A random walk on this graph will have a stationary distribution that assigns large probabilities to the terms in the centers of the clusters.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] This is similar to densely connected Web pages getting ranked highly by PageRank.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] This approach has also been used in document summarization, considered below.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Like keyphrase extraction, document summarization aims to identify the essence of a text.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The only real difference is that now we are dealing with larger text units—whole sentences instead of words and phrases.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Supervised text summarization is very much like supervised keyphrase extraction.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Basically, if you have a collection of documents and human-generated summaries for them, you can learn features of sentences that make them good candidates for inclusion in the summary.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Features might include the position in the document (i.e., the first few sentences are probably important), the number of words in the sentence, etc.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The main difficulty in supervised extractive summarization is that the known summaries must be manually created by extracting sentences so the sentences in an original training document can be labeled as "in summary" or "not in summary".
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] This is not typically how people create summaries, so simply using journal abstracts or existing summaries is usually not sufficient.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The sentences in these summaries do not necessarily match up with sentences in the original text, so it would be difficult to assign labels to examples for training.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Note, however, that these natural summaries can still be used for evaluation purposes, since ROUGE-1 evaluation only considers unigrams.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] During the DUC 2001 and 2002 evaluation workshops, TNO developed a sentence extraction system for multi-document summarization in the news domain.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The system was based on a hybrid system using a Naive Bayes classifier and statistical language models for modeling salience.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Although the system exhibited good results, the researchers wanted to explore the effectiveness of a maximum entropy (ME) classifier for the meeting summarization task, as ME is known to be robust against feature dependencies.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Maximum entropy has also been applied successfully for summarization in the broadcast news domain.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] A promising approach is adaptive document/text summarization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] It involves first recognizing the text genre and then applying summarization algorithms optimized for this genre.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The unsupervised approach to summarization is also quite similar in spirit to unsupervised keyphrase extraction and gets around the issue of costly training data.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Some unsupervised summarization approaches are based on finding a "centroid" sentence, which is the mean word vector of all the sentences in the document.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Then the sentences can be ranked with regard to their similarity to this centroid sentence.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] A more principled way to estimate sentence importance is using random walks and eigenvector centrality.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] LexRank is an algorithm essentially identical to TextRank, and both use this approach for document summarization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The two methods were developed by different groups at the same time, and LexRank simply focused on summarization, but could just as easily be used for keyphrase extraction or any other NLP ranking task.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In both LexRank and TextRank, a graph is constructed by creating a vertex for each sentence in the document.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The edges between sentences are based on some form of semantic similarity or content overlap.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] While LexRank uses cosine similarity of TF-IDF vectors, TextRank uses a very similar measure based on the number of words two sentences have in common (normalized by the sentences' lengths).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The LexRank paper explored using unweighted edges after applying a threshold to the cosine values, but also experimented with using edges with weights equal to the similarity score.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] TextRank uses continuous similarity scores as weights.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In both algorithms, the sentences are ranked by applying PageRank to the resulting graph.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] A summary is formed by combining the top ranking sentences, using a threshold or length cutoff to limit the size of the summary.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In this case, some training documents might be needed, though the TextRank results show the additional features are not absolutely necessary.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Unlike TextRank, LexRank has been applied to multi-document summarization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Multi-document summarization creates information reports that are both concise and comprehensive.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] With different opinions being put together and outlined, every topic is described from multiple perspectives within a single document.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Automatic summaries present information extracted from multiple sources algorithmically, without any editorial touch or subjective human intervention, thus making it completely unbiased.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Multi-document extractive summarization faces a problem of redundancy.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Ideally, we want to extract sentences that are both "central" (i.e., contain the main ideas) and "diverse" (i.e., they differ from one another).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For example, in a set of news articles about some event, each article is likely to have many similar sentences.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] To address this issue, LexRank applies a heuristic post-processing step that adds sentences in rank order, but discards sentences that are too similar to ones already in the summary.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] This method is called Cross-Sentence Information Subsumption (CSIS).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] These methods work based on the idea that sentences "recommend" other similar sentences to the reader.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Thus, if one sentence is very similar to many others, it will likely be a sentence of great importance.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Its importance also stems from the importance of the sentences "recommending" it.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Thus, to get ranked highly and placed in a summary, a sentence must be similar to many sentences that are in turn also similar to many other sentences.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] This makes intuitive sense and allows the algorithms to be applied to an arbitrary new text.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The methods are domain-independent and easily portable.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] One could imagine the features indicating important sentences in the news domain might vary considerably from the biomedical domain.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] However, the unsupervised "recommendation"-based approach applies to any domain.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In addition to explicitly promoting diversity during the ranking process, GRASSHOPPER incorporates a prior ranking (based on sentence position in the case of summarization).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The state of the art results for multi-document summarization are obtained using mixtures of submodular functions.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] These methods have achieved the state of the art results for Document Summarization Corpora, DUC 04 - 07.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Similar results were achieved with the use of determinantal point processes (which are a special case of submodular functions) for DUC-04.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] A new method for multi-lingual multi-document summarization that avoids redundancy generates ideograms to represent the meaning of each sentence in each document, then evaluates similarity by comparing ideogram shape and position.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] It does not use word frequency, training or preprocessing.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] It uses two user-supplied parameters: equivalence (when are two sentences to be considered equivalent?) and relevance (how long is the desired summary?).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The idea of a submodular set function has recently emerged as a powerful modeling tool for various summarization problems.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Submodular functions naturally model notions of *coverage*, *information*, *representation* and *diversity*.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Moreover, several important combinatorial optimization problems occur as special instances of submodular optimization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For example, the set cover problem is a special case of submodular optimization, since the set cover function is submodular.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The set cover function attempts to find a subset of objects which *cover* a given set of concepts.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For example, in document summarization, one would like the summary to cover all important and relevant concepts in the document.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Similarly, the facility location problem is a special case of submodular functions.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The Facility Location function also naturally models coverage and diversity.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Another example of a submodular optimization problem is using a determinantal point process to model diversity.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Similarly, the Maximum-Marginal-Relevance procedure can also be seen as an instance of submodular optimization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] All these important models encouraging coverage, diversity and information are all submodular.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Moreover, submodular functions can be efficiently combined, and the resulting function is still submodular.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Hence, one could combine one submodular function which models diversity, another one which models coverage and use human supervision to learn a right model of a submodular function for the problem.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] While submodular functions are fitting problems for summarization, they also admit very efficient algorithms for optimization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For example, a simple greedy algorithm admits a constant factor guarantee.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Moreover, the greedy algorithm is extremely simple to implement and can scale to large datasets, which is very important for summarization problems.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Submodular functions have achieved state-of-the-art for almost all summarization problems.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For example, work by Lin and Bilmes, 2012 shows that submodular functions achieve the best results to date on DUC-04, DUC-05, DUC-06 and DUC-07 systems for document summarization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Similarly, work by Lin and Bilmes, 2011, shows that many existing systems for automatic summarization are instances of submodular functions.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] This was a breakthrough result establishing submodular functions as the right models for summarization problems.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Submodular Functions have also been used for other summarization tasks.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Tschiatschek et al., 2014 show that mixtures of submodular functions achieve state-of-the-art results for image collection summarization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Similarly, Bairi et al., 2015 show the utility of submodular functions for summarizing multi-document topic hierarchies.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Submodular Functions have also successfully been used for summarizing machine learning datasets.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The most common way to evaluate the informativeness of automatic summaries is to compare them with human-made model summaries.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Evaluation can be intrinsic or extrinsic, and inter-textual or intra-textual.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Intrinsic evaluation assesses the summaries directly, while extrinsic evaluation evaluates how the summarization system affects the completion of some other task.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Intrinsic evaluations have assessed mainly the coherence and informativeness of summaries.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Extrinsic evaluations, on the other hand, have tested the impact of summarization on tasks like relevance assessment, reading comprehension, etc.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Intra-textual evaluation assess the output of a specific summarization system, while inter-textual evaluation focuses on contrastive analysis of outputs of several summarization systems.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Human judgement often varies greatly in what it considers a "good" summary, so creating an automatic evaluation process is particularly difficult.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Manual evaluation can be used, but this is both time and labor-intensive, as it requires humans to read not only the summaries but also the source documents.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Other issues are those concerning coherence and coverage.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The most common way to evaluate summaries is ROUGE (Recall-Oriented Understudy for Gisting Evaluation).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] It is very common for summarization and translation systems in NIST's Document Understanding Conferences.[2] ROUGE is a recall-based measure of how well a summary covers the content of human-generated summaries known as references.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] It calculates n-gram overlaps between automatically generated summaries and previously written human summaries.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] It is recall-based to encourage inclusion of all important topics in summaries.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Recall can be computed with respect to unigram, bigram, trigram, or 4-gram matching.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] For example, ROUGE-1 is the fraction of unigrams that appear in both the reference summary and the automatic summary out of all unigrams in the reference summary.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] If there are multiple reference summaries, their scores are averaged.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] A high level of overlap should indicate a high degree of shared concepts between the two summaries.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] ROUGE cannot determine if the result is coherent, that is if sentences flow together in a sensibly.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] High-order n-gram ROUGE measures help to some degree.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Another unsolved problem is Anaphor resolution.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Similarly, for image summarization, Tschiatschek et al., developed a Visual-ROUGE score which judges the performance of algorithms for image summarization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Domain-independent summarization techniques apply sets of general features to identify information-rich text segments.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Recent research focuses on domain-specific summarization using knowledge specific to the text's domain, such as medical knowledge and ontologies for summarizing medical texts.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The main drawback of the evaluation systems so far is that we need a reference summary (for some methods, more than one), to compare automatic summaries with models.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Much effort has to be made to create corpora of texts and their corresponding summaries.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Furthermore, some methods require manual annotation of the summaries (e.g.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Moreover, they all perform a quantitative evaluation with regard to different similarity metrics.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] The first publication in the area dates back to 1957 (Hans Peter Luhn), starting with a statistical technique.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Research increased significantly in 2015.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Term frequency–inverse document frequency had been used by 2016.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Pattern-based summarization was the most powerful option for multi-document summarization found by 2016.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] In the following year it was surpassed by latent semantic analysis (LSA) combined with non-negative matrix factorization (NMF).
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Although they did not replace other approaches and are often combined with them, by 2019 machine learning methods dominated the extractive summarization of single documents, which was considered to be nearing maturity.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] By 2020, the field was still very active and research is shifting towards abstractive summation and real-time summarization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] Recently the rise of transformer models replacing more traditional RNN (LSTM) have provided a flexibility in the mapping of text sequences to text sequences of a different type, which is well suited to automatic summarization.
[src:chain-of-density/automatic-summarization] This includes models such as T5 and Pegasus.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] It can also be defined as the practice of designing and refining input instructions given to a generative AI model to produce more accurate, relevant, or useful outputs.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Effective prompt engineering involves understanding how a model interprets language, and may include techniques such as few-shot prompting, chain-of-thought prompting, and role assignment.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] It is increasingly considered a skill for working with large language models (LLMs) in both research and professional contexts.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] During the 2020s AI boom, prompt engineering became regarded as a business capability across corporations and industries.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Employees with the title **prompt engineer** were hired to create prompts that would increase productivity and efficacy, although the individual title has since lost traction amid AI models that produce better prompts than humans and corporate training in prompting for general employees.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Common prompting techniques include multi-shot, chain-of-thought, and tree-of-thought prompting, as well as assigning roles to the model.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Automated prompt generation methods, such as retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), provide for greater accuracy and a wider scope of functions for prompt engineers.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Prompt injection is a type of cybersecurity attack that targets machine learning models through malicious prompts.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] A prompt is some natural language text that describes and prescribes the task that an artificial intelligence (AI) should perform.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] A prompt for a text-to-text language model can be a query, a command, or a longer statement referencing context, instructions, and conversation history.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] The process of prompt engineering may involve designing clear queries, refining wording, providing relevant context, specifying the style of output, and assigning a character for the AI to mimic in order to guide the model toward more accurate, useful, and consistent responses.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] When communicating with a text-to-image or a text-to-audio model, a typical prompt contains a description of a desired output such as "a high-quality photo of an astronaut riding a horse" or "Lo-fi slow BPM electro chill with organic samples".
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Prompt engineering may be applied to text-to-image models to achieve a desired subject, style, layout, lighting, and aesthetic.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Common terms used to describe various specific prompt engineering techniques include *chain-of-thought*, *tree-of-thought*, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] A 2024 survey of the field identified over 50 distinct text-based prompting techniques, 40 multimodal variants, and a vocabulary of 33 terms used across prompting research, highlighting a present lack of standardised terminology for prompt engineering.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Vibe coding is an AI-assisted software development method where a user prompts an LLM with a description of what they want and lets it generate or edit the code.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] In 2025, "vibe coding" was the Collins Dictionary word of the year.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Context engineering is a related process that focuses on the context elements that accompany user prompts, which include system instructions, retrieved knowledge, tool definitions, conversation summaries, and task metadata.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Context engineering is performed to improve reliability, provenance and token efficiency in production LLM systems.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] The concept emphasises operational practices such as token budgeting, provenance tags, versioning of context artifacts, observability (logging which context was supplied), and context regression tests to ensure that changes to supplied context do not silently alter system behaviour.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Research has found that the performance of large language models (LLMs) is highly sensitive to choices such as the ordering of examples, the quality of demonstration labels, and even small variations in phrasing.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] In some cases, reordering examples in a prompt produced accuracy shifts of more than 40 percent.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] A model's ability to temporarily learn from prompts is known as *in-context learning*.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] In-context learning is an emergent ability of large language models.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] It is an emergent property of model scale, meaning that breaks in scaling laws occur, leading to its efficacy increasing at a different rate in larger models than in smaller models.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Unlike training and fine-tuning, which produce lasting changes, in-context learning is temporary.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Training models to perform in-context learning can be viewed as a form of meta-learning, or "learning to learn".
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Research consistently demonstrates that LLMs are highly sensitive to subtle variations in prompt formatting, structure, and linguistic properties.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Some studies have shown up to 76 accuracy points across formatting changes in few-shot settings.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Linguistic features significantly influence prompt effectiveness—such as morphology, syntax, and lexico-semantic changes—which meaningfully enhance task performance across a variety of tasks.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Clausal syntax, for example, improves consistency and reduces uncertainty in knowledge retrieval.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] This sensitivity persists even with larger model sizes, additional few-shot examples, or instruction tuning.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] To address sensitivity of models and make them more robust, several evaluative methods have been proposed.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] FormatSpread facilitates systematic analysis by evaluating a range of plausible prompt formats, offering a more comprehensive performance interval.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Similarly, PromptEval estimates performance distributions across diverse prompts, enabling robust metrics such as performance quantiles and accurate evaluations under constrained budgets.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] A prompt may include a few examples for a model to learn from in-context, an implementation of few-shot learning for LLMs.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] It is possible to fine-tune models on CoT reasoning datasets to enhance this capability further and stimulate better interpretability.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] As originally proposed by Google, each CoT prompt is accompanied by a set of input/output examples—called *exemplars*—to demonstrate the desired model output, making it a few-shot prompting technique.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] However, according to a later paper from researchers at Google and the University of Tokyo, simply appending the words "Let's think step-by-step" was also effective, which allowed for CoT to be employed as a zero-shot technique.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] In 2022, text-to-image models like DALL-E 2, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney were released to the public.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] These models take text prompts as input and use them to generate images.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Early text-to-image models typically do not understand negation, grammar and sentence structure in the same way as large language models, and may thus require a different set of prompting techniques.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] The prompt "a party with no cake" may produce an image including a cake.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] A text-to-image prompt commonly includes a description of the subject of the art, the desired medium (such as *digital painting* or *photography*), style (such as *hyperrealistic* or *pop-art*), lighting (such as *rim lighting* or *crepuscular rays*), color, and texture.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Word order also affects the output of a text-to-image prompt.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Words closer to the start of a prompt may be emphasized more heavily.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Some text-to-image models are capable of imitating the style of particular artists by name.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] For example, the phrase *in the style of Greg Rutkowski* has been used in Stable Diffusion and Midjourney prompts to generate images in the distinctive style of Polish digital artist Greg Rutkowski.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Famous artists such as Vincent van Gogh and Salvador Dalí have also been used for styling and testing.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] For text-to-image models, *textual inversion* performs an optimization process to create a new word embedding based on a set of example images.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] This embedding vector acts as a "pseudo-word" which can be included in a prompt to express the content or style of the examples.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] In 2023, Meta's AI research released Segment Anything, a computer vision model that can perform image segmentation by prompting.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] As an alternative to text prompts, Segment Anything can accept bounding boxes, segmentation masks, and foreground/background points.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] The process of writing and refining a prompt for an LLM or generative AI shares some parallels with an iterative engineering design process, such as by discovering reusable best practices through reproducible experimentation.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] However, several fundamental limitations constrain its reliability as a discipline.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Effective prompting strategies are highly model specific, a technique that improves performance on one model may degrade it on another, making generalization difficult.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Prompts are also brittle: minor surface-level changes in phrasing, punctuation, or word order can produce dramatically different outputs, even when the semantic intent remains identical.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] This instability makes it difficult to establish durable, transferable prompt patterns across deployment contexts.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Furthermore, as AI models continue to improve in their ability to interpret user intent directly, many manual prompting techniques are becoming obsolete.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Advances in instruction-following and model reasoning have reduced the marginal value of elaborate prompt construction for everyday tasks, raising questions about the long-term viability of prompt engineering as a standalone discipline.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Recent research has explored automated prompt engineering, using optimization algorithms to generate or refine prompts without human intervention.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] These automated approaches aim to identify effective prompt patterns by analyzing model gradients, reinforcement feedback, or evolutionary processes, reducing the need for manual experimentation.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Retrieval-augmented generation is a technique that enables GenAI models to retrieve and incorporate new information.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] It modifies interactions with an LLM so that the model responds to user queries with reference to a specified set of documents, using this information to supplement information from its pre-existing training data.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] This allows LLMs to use domain-specific and/or updated information.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] RAG improves large language models by incorporating information retrieval before generating responses.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Unlike traditional LLMs that rely on static training data, RAG pulls relevant text from databases, uploaded documents, or web sources.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] By dynamically retrieving information, RAG enables AI to generate more accurate responses and fewer AI hallucinations without frequent retraining.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] GraphRAG (coined by Microsoft Research) is a technique that extends RAG with the use of a knowledge graph to allow the model to connect disparate pieces of information, synthesize insights, and understand summarized semantic concepts over large data collections.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] It was shown to be effective on datasets like the Violent Incident Information from News Articles.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] LLMs themselves can be used to compose prompts for LLMs.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] CoT examples can be generated by LLM themselves.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] In "auto-CoT", a library of questions are converted to vectors by a model such as BERT.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Questions close to the centroid of each cluster are selected, in order to have a subset of diverse questions.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] An LLM does zero-shot CoT on each selected question.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] The question and the corresponding CoT answer are added to a dataset of demonstrations.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] These diverse demonstrations can then added to prompts for few-shot learning.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] In "prefix-tuning", "prompt tuning", or "soft prompting", floating-point vectors are searched directly by gradient descent to maximize the log-likelihood on outputs.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] An earlier result uses the same idea of gradient descent search, but is designed for masked language models like BERT, and searches only over token sequences, rather than numerical vectors.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Formally, it searches for $\arg \max _{\tilde {X}}\sum _{i}\log Pr[Y^{i}|{\tilde {X}}\ast X^{i}]$ where ${\tilde {X}}$ ranges over token sequences of a specified length.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Early precedents of structured user interaction with ruled-based AI systems can be found in enterprise automation software from 1990s.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] For example, The Intelligent Filling Manager (1999), developed by Krishna C.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Mukherjee, used a dynamic Q&A interface driven by rule-based expert system to collect user inputs for generating regulatory filings automatically across jurisdictions.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] While not involving neural networks, such systems featured prompt-like workflows that influenced later human-in-the-loop AI designs.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] In 2018, researchers first proposed that all previously separate tasks in natural language processing (NLP) could be cast as question-answer problems over a context.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] The AI boom saw an increased focus within academic literature and professional practice on applying prompting techniques to get the model to output the desired outcome and avoid nonsensical output, a process characterized by trial-and-error.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] According to *The Wall Street Journal* in 2025, the job of prompt engineer was one of the hottest in 2023, but has become obsolete due to models that better intuit user intent and to company trainings.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] A repository for prompts reported that over 2,000 public prompts for around 170 datasets were available in February 2022.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] In 2022, the *chain-of-thought* prompting technique was proposed by Google researchers.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] In 2023, several text-to-text and text-to-image prompt databases were made publicly available.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] The Personalized Image-Prompt (PIP) dataset, a generated image-text dataset that has been categorized by 3,115 users, has also been made available publicly in 2024.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] Prompt injection is a cybersecurity exploit in which adversaries craft inputs that appear legitimate but are designed to cause unintended behavior in machine learning models, particularly large language models.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] This attack takes advantage of the model's inability to distinguish between developer-defined prompts and user inputs, allowing adversaries to bypass safeguards and influence model behaviour.
[src:chain-of-density/chain-of-thought-prompting] While LLMs are designed to follow trusted instructions, they can be manipulated into carrying out unintended responses through carefully crafted inputs.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:chain-of-density/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] In this example, a person name consisting of one token, a two-token company name and a temporal expression have been detected and classified.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] In the expression *named entity*, the word *named* restricts the task to those entities for which one or many strings, such as words or phrases, stand (fairly) consistently for some referent.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] This is closely related to rigid designators, as defined by Saul Kripke, although in practice NER deals with many names and referents that are not philosophically "rigid".
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] For instance, the *automotive company created by Henry Ford in 1903* can be referred to as *Ford* or *Ford Motor Company*, although "Ford" can refer to many other entities as well (see Ford).
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Full named-entity recognition is often broken down, conceptually and possibly also in implementations, as two distinct problems: detection of names, and classification of the names by the type of entity they refer to (e.g. person, organization, or location).
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] The first phase is typically simplified to a segmentation problem: names are defined to be contiguous spans of tokens, with no nesting, so that "Bank of America" is a single name, disregarding the fact that inside this name, the substring "America" is itself a name.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] This segmentation problem is formally similar to chunking.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] The second phase requires choosing an ontology by which to organize categories of things.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Temporal expressions and some numerical expressions (e.g., money, percentages, etc.) may also be considered as named entities in the context of the NER task.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] While some instances of these types are good examples of rigid designators (e.g., the year 2001) there are also many invalid ones (e.g., I take my vacations in “June”).
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] In the first case, the year *2001* refers to the *2001st year of the Gregorian calendar*.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] In the second case, the month *June* may refer to the month of an undefined year (*past June*, *next June*, *every June*, etc.).
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] It is arguable that the definition of *named entity* is loosened in such cases for practical reasons.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] The definition of the term *named entity* is therefore not strict and often has to be explained in the context in which it is used.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Certain hierarchies of named entity types have been proposed in the literature.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] BBN categories, proposed in 2002, are used for *question answering* and consists of 29 types and 64 subtypes.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Sekine's extended hierarchy, proposed in 2002, is made of 200 subtypes.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] More recently, in 2011 Ritter used a hierarchy based on common Freebase entity types in ground-breaking experiments on NER over social media text.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] NER can have reference resolution ambiguities where the same name can refer to different entities of the same type.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] For example, "JFK" can refer to the former president of the United States or his son.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] The same name can refer to completely different types.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] "JFK" might refer to the airport in New York.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] "IRA" can refer to Individual Retirement Account, International Reading Association or Irish Republican Army.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] For example, "The White House" can refer to an organization instead of a location.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] To evaluate the quality of an NER system's output, several measures have been defined.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] The usual measures are called precision, recall, and F1 score.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] However, several issues remain in just how to calculate those values.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] These statistical measures work reasonably well for the obvious cases of finding or missing a real entity exactly; and for finding a non-entity.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] However, NER can fail in many other ways, many of which are arguably "partially correct", and should not be counted as complete success or failures.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] One overly simple method of measuring accuracy is merely to count what fraction of all tokens in the text were correctly or incorrectly identified as part of entity references (or as being entities of the correct type).
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] It follows from the above definition that any prediction that misses a single token, includes a spurious token, or has the wrong class, is a hard error and does not contribute positively to either precision or recall.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Thus, this measure may be said to be pessimistic: it can be the case that many "errors" are close to correct, and might be adequate for a given purpose.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] For example, one system might always omit titles such as "Ms." or "Ph.D.", but be compared to a system or ground-truth data that expects titles to be included.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] In that case, every such name is treated as an error.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Because of such issues, it is important actually to examine the kinds of errors, and decide how important they are given one's goals and requirements.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Evaluation models based on a token-by-token matching have been proposed.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Such models may be given partial credit for overlapping matches (such as using the Intersection over Union criterion).
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] They allow a finer grained evaluation and comparison of extraction systems.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] NER systems have been created that use linguistic grammar-based techniques as well as statistical models such as machine learning.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] State of the art systems may incorporate multiple approaches.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Hand-crafted grammar-based systems typically obtain better precision, but at the cost of lower recall and months of work by experienced computational linguists.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Statistical NER systems typically require a large amount of manually annotated training data.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Semisupervised approaches have been suggested to avoid part of the annotation effort.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] In the statistical learning era, NER was usually performed by learning a simple linear regression model on engineered features, then decoded by a bidirectional Viterbi algorithm.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] A **gazetteer** is a list of names and their types, such as "General Electric".
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] It can be used to augment any system for NER.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] They had been often used in the era of statistical machine learning.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Many different classifier types have been used to perform machine-learned NER, with conditional random fields being a typical choice.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Transformers features token classification using deep learning models.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Early work in NER systems in the 1990s was aimed primarily at extraction from journalistic articles.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Attention then turned to processing of military dispatches and reports.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Later stages of the automatic content extraction (ACE) evaluation also included several types of informal text styles, such as weblogs and text transcripts from conversational telephone speech conversations.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Since about 1998, there has been a great deal of interest in entity identification in the molecular biology, bioinformatics, and medical natural language processing communities.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] The most common entity of interest in that domain has been names of genes and gene products.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] There has been also considerable interest in the recognition of chemical entities and drugs in the context of the CHEMDNER competition, with 27 teams participating in this task.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] In 2001, research indicated that even state-of-the-art NER systems were brittle, meaning that NER systems developed for one domain did not typically perform well on other domains.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Considerable effort is involved in tuning NER systems to perform well in a new domain; this is true for both rule-based and trainable statistical systems.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] As of 2007, state-of-the-art NER systems for English produce near-human performance.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] For example, the best system entering MUC-7 scored 93.39% of F-measure while human annotators scored 97.60% and 96.95%.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Despite high F1 numbers reported on the MUC-7 dataset, the problem of named-entity recognition is far from being solved.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] The main efforts are directed to reducing the annotations labor by employing semi-supervised learning, robust performance across domains and scaling up to fine-grained entity types.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] In recent years, many projects have turned to crowdsourcing, which is a promising solution to obtain high-quality aggregate human judgments for supervised and semi-supervised machine learning approaches to NER.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Another challenging task is devising models to deal with linguistically complex contexts such as Twitter and search queries.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] There are some researchers who did some comparisons about the NER performances from different statistical models such as HMM (hidden Markov model), ME (maximum entropy), and CRF (conditional random fields), and feature sets.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] And some researchers recently proposed graph-based semi-supervised learning model for language specific NER tasks.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] A recently emerging task of identifying "important expressions" in text and cross-linking them to Wikipedia can be seen as an instance of extremely fine-grained named-entity recognition, where the types are the actual Wikipedia pages describing the (potentially ambiguous) concepts.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] Another field that has seen progress but remains challenging is the application of NER to Twitter and other microblogs, considered "noisy" due to non-standard orthography, shortness and informality of texts.
[src:chain-of-density/named-entity-recognition] NER challenges in English Tweets have been organized by research communities to compare performances of various approaches, such as bidirectional LSTMs, Learning-to-Search, or CRFs.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Compare speech segmentation, the process of dividing speech into linguistically meaningful portions.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Word segmentation is the problem of dividing a string of written language into its component words.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] In English and many other languages using some form of the Latin alphabet, the space is a good approximation of a word divider (word delimiter), although this concept has limits because of the variability with which languages emically regard collocations and compounds.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] In contrast, German compound nouns show less orthographic variation, with solidification being a stronger norm.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] However, the equivalent to the word space character is not found in all written scripts, and without it word segmentation is a difficult problem.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Languages which do not have a trivial word segmentation process include Chinese, Japanese, where sentences but not words are delimited, Thai and Lao, where phrases and sentences but not words are delimited, and Vietnamese, where syllables but not words are delimited.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] In some writing systems however, such as the Ge'ez script used for Amharic and Tigrinya among other languages, words are explicitly delimited (at least historically) with a non-whitespace character.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] The Unicode Consortium has published a *Standard Annex on Text Segmentation*, exploring the issues of segmentation in multiscript texts.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Word splitting may also refer to the process of hyphenation.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Some scholars have suggested that modern Chinese should be written in word segmentation, with spaces between words like written English.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Because there are ambiguous texts where only the author knows the intended meaning.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] For example, "美国会不同意。" may mean "美国 会 不同意。" (The US will not agree.) or "美 国会 不同意。" (The US Congress does not agree).
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] For more details, see Chinese word-segmented writing.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Intent segmentation is the problem of dividing written words into keyphrases (2 or more group of words).
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] In English and all other languages the core intent or desire is identified and become the corner-stone of the keyphrase Intent segmentation.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Core product/service, idea, action & or thought anchor the keyphrase.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Sentence segmentation is the problem of dividing a string of written language into its component sentences.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] In English and some other languages, using punctuation, particularly the full stop/period character is a reasonable approximation.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] However even in English this problem is not trivial due to the use of the full stop character for abbreviations, which may or may not also terminate a sentence.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] For example, *Mr.* is not its own sentence in "*Mr.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Smith went to the shops in Jones Street."* When processing plain text, tables of abbreviations that contain periods can help prevent incorrect assignment of sentence boundaries.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] As with word segmentation, not all written languages contain punctuation characters that are useful for approximating sentence boundaries.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Topic analysis consists of two main tasks: topic identification and text segmentation.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] While the first is a simple classification of a specific text, the latter case implies that a document may contain multiple topics, and the task of computerized text segmentation may be to discover these topics automatically and segment the text accordingly.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] The topic boundaries may be apparent from section titles and paragraphs.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] In other cases, one needs to use techniques similar to those used in document classification.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] It is also needed in topic detection and tracking systems and text summarizing problems.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Many different approaches have been tried: e.g.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] HMM, lexical chains, passage similarity using word co-occurrence, clustering, topic modeling, etc.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] It is quite an ambiguous task – people evaluating the text segmentation systems often differ in topic boundaries.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Hence, text segment evaluation is also a challenging problem.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Processes may be required to segment text into segments besides mentioned, including morphemes (a task usually called morphological analysis) or paragraphs.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Automatic segmentation is the problem in natural language processing of implementing a computer process to segment text.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] When punctuation and similar clues are not consistently available, the segmentation task often requires fairly non-trivial techniques, such as statistical decision-making, large dictionaries, as well as consideration of syntactic and semantic constraints.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Effective natural language processing systems and text segmentation tools usually operate on text in specific domains and sources.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] As an example, processing text used in medical records is a very different problem than processing news articles or real estate advertisements.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] The process of developing text segmentation tools starts with collecting a large corpus of text in an application domain.
[src:chain-of-density/text-segmentation] Some text segmentation systems take advantage of any markup like HTML and know document formats like PDF to provide additional evidence for sentence and paragraph boundaries.
